<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-026-252 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 471 061</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Oct 29 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Dragon shows speech recognition system in five languages. (DragonSystems Inc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Buckler, Grant.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Dragon Systems Inc. (Product development).andO;Topic:     Product DevelopmentVoice recognitionVoice I/O equipment.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Dragon Shows Speech Recognition System In Five Languages 10/29/91 NEWTON,MASSACHUSETTS, U.S.A., 1991 OCT 29 (NB) -- Dragon Systems, manufacturer ofthe DragonDictate speech recognition system, recently showed five prototypesystems that recognize speech in several major European languages.andP;  Thesystems have vocabularies of 7,000 to 8,000 words in Dutch, French, German,Italian, and Spanish.andM;Dragon is aiming to offer the same level of speech recognition in those fivelanguages that its DragonDictate-30K product currently provides in English.andO;DragonDictate-30K has a vocabulary of about 30,000 English words.andM;Ellen Dorian, marketing coordinator at Dragon Systems, told Newsbytes thatwhile speech recognition systems already exist for some European languages,there are none commercially available to her company's knowledge that offerthe vocabulary of DragonDictate-30K.andM;The DragonDictate-30K system includes a digital signal processing card thatfits in a full-length expansion slot in an IBM or compatible PC, along withspeech recognition software.andM;It requires a PC with an Intel 80386 or 80486 processor running at no lessthan 20 (megahertz) MHz, eight megabytes (MB) of memory, and at least 10MB offree disk space to support one user.andP;  For each additional user the systemneeds two to three MB of additional disk space, Dorian said.andP;  The systemadapts to different speakers with little or no initial training.andM;Dragon Systems noted that some languages are harder than others to recognizeby machine.andP;  The Germanic languages -- English, Dutch, and German -- requiremore phonemes, or units of speech, than Romance languages such as French,Spanish, and Italian.andP;  The large number of inflected forms in Italian, andthe many compound words in German, may also mean those languages requirelarger vocabularies to achieve the same results, the company claims.andM;Dragon Systems hopes to release its first European-language products nextyear.andP;  The company said it is also working on British-English,French-Canadian, and Japanese versions of DragonDictate.andM;(Grant Buckler/19911029/Press Contact: Ellen Dorian, Dragon Systems,617-965-5200, fax 617-527-0372)</TEXT></DOC>